name: Nome
etymology: Named for the town of Nome, Alaska. In turn, the city’s name “Nome” is debated; there are three theories. The first is that the name was given by Nome’s founder, Jafet Lindeberg, an immigrant from Norway. Nome appears as a toponym in several places in Norway. A second theory is that Nome received its name through an error: allegedly when a British cartographer copied an ambiguous annotation made by a British officer on a nautical chart, while on a voyage up the Bering Strait. The officer had written “? Name” next to the unnamed cape. The mapmaker misread the annotation as “C. Nome”, or Cape Nome, and used that name on his own chart; the city in turn took its name from the cape. The third proposed origin of the name is from a misunderstanding of the local Inupiaq word for “Where at?”, Naami.

name: Grant

name: Montgomery

name: Robertson
etymology: Named for James Robertson, explorer, soldier and Indian agent.

name: Cocke
etymology: Named for William Cocke (1747–1828), one of Tennessee’s first U.S. senators.

name: Smith
etymology: Named for Revolutionary War officer and U.S. Senator Daniel Smith.

name: Williamson
etymology: Named for U.S. Representative Hugh Williamson.

name: Wilson
etymology: Named for David Wilson, a member of the legislatures of North Carolina and the Southwest Territory.

name: Anderson
etymology: Named for Joseph Anderson, a U.S. senator from Tennessee.

name: Claiborne
etymology: Named for William C. C. Claiborne (1775–1817), Governor of Louisiana and Governor of Mississippi Territory.

name: Jackson
etymology: Named for Andrew Jackson, the 7th President of the United States.

name: Roane
etymology: Named for Archibald Roane, second Governor of Tennessee.

name: Dickson
etymology: Named for U.S. Representative William Dickson (1770–1816).

name: Rutherford
etymology: Named for Griffith Rutherford, Revolutionary War soldier.

name: Stewart
etymology: Named for Duncan Stewart, Tennessee state legislator and lieutenant governor of Mississippi Territory.

name: Campbell
etymology: Named for Arthur Campbell, a Virginia House of Burgesses representative.

name: Overton
etymology: Named for John Overton, judge, planter, politician and banker.

name: White
etymology: Named for John White, Revolutionary War soldier and the first white settler in the county.

name: Bedford
etymology: Named for Thomas Bedford, a soldier in the Revolutionary War.

name: Bledsoe
etymology: Named for Anthony Bledsoe, a soldier in the Revolutionary War and an early settler in the area.

name: Franklin
etymology: Named for Benjamin Franklin (1706–1790), one of the Founding Fathers of the United States.

name: Hickman
etymology: Named for Edwin Hickman, a longhunter killed by Native Americans near present-day Centerville, Tennessee.

name: Maury
etymology: Named for Abram Poindexter Maury, Sr., a pioneer, farmer, and state senator.

name: Rhea
etymology: Named for John Rhea, Irish-American Revolutionary War soldier and Congressman.

name: Warren
etymology: Named for Joseph Warren, Revolutionary War leader.

name: Giles
etymology: Named for William Branch Giles, 24th Governor of Virginia (1827–1830).

name: Humphreys
etymology: Named for Parry Wayne Humphreys (1778–1839), U.S. Representative from Tennessee.

name: Lincoln
etymology: Named for Benjamin Lincoln, a leading general in the American Revolutionary War and the first U.S. Secretary of War.

name: Lawrence
etymology: Named for James Lawrence, a captain in the United States Navy and hero of the War of 1812.

name: Marion
etymology: Named for Francis Marion, a Continental Army officer nicknamed the “Swamp Fox” for his activity in the Southern Theater of the American Revolutionary War.

name: Morgan
etymology: Named for Daniel Morgan, an officer during the American Revolutionary War and a U.S. representative.

name: Wayne
etymology: Named for Revolutionary War general Anthony Wayne.

name: Hamilton
etymology: Named for Alexander Hamilton (1757–1804), first United States Secretary of the Treasury and one of the Founding Fathers.

name: Hardin
etymology: Named for Joseph Hardin, a legislator of the Southwest Territory and the State of Franklin.

name: McMinn
etymology: Named for Joseph McMinn, speaker of the state senate and governor of Tennessee.

name: Monroe
etymology: Named for James Monroe, the 5th President of the United States.

name: Perry
etymology: Named for naval officer Oliver Hazard Perry.

name: Shelby
etymology: Named for Isaac Shelby, the first Governor of Kentucky.

name: Carroll
etymology: Named for William Carroll, the sixth governor of Tennessee.

name: Henderson
etymology: Named for James Henderson, commander of Tennessee troops preceding the Battle of New Orleans.

name: Henry
etymology: Named for Patrick Henry, Revolutionary War patriot and first post-colonial Governor of Virginia (1776–1779).

name: Madison
etymology: Named for James Madison, the 4th President of the United States.

name: Dyer
etymology: Named for Tennessee state legislator Robert Henry Dyer.

name: Fentress
etymology: Named for James Fentress, a Tennessee state legislator.

name: Gibson
etymology: Named for John H. Gibson, a soldier of the Natchez Expedition and the Creek War.

name: Hardeman
etymology: Named for Thomas Jones Hardeman, a soldier during the Creek War and War of 1812, and later a member of the Republic of Texas legislature.

name: Haywood
etymology: Named for Judge John Haywood (1762–1826), called “the father of Tennessee history”.

name: McNairy
etymology: Named for John McNairy, a Constitutional Convention delegate and U.S. district judge for Tennessee.

name: Tipton
etymology: Named for Jacob Tipton, who was killed by Native Americans in a conflict over the Northwest Territory.

name: Weakley
etymology: Named for U.S. Representative Robert Weakley.

name: Fayette
etymology: From La Fayette, the original spelling for the title used by Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette (1757–1834), a French general who played a major role in the Revolutionary War.

name: Benton
etymology: Named for either David Benton, a soldier in the colonial Tennessee Militia; or Thomas Hart Benton, a U.S. senator from Missouri who pushed for westward expansion of the United States.

name: Lauderdale
etymology: Named for Colonel James Lauderdale, who died during the first Battle of New Orleans.

name: Bradley
etymology: Named for Edward Bradley, a Tennessee militia officer in the War of 1812.

name: Cannon
etymology: Named for Newton Cannon, the tenth governor of Tennessee.

name: Coffee
etymology: Named for John Coffee (1772–1833), frontiersman, planter, and veteran of the Creek War and War of 1812.

name: Johnson
etymology: Named for Thomas Johnson, an early settler of the area.

name: Marshall
etymology: Named for John Marshall, the 4th Chief Justice of the Supreme Court and the 4th U.S. Secretary of State.

name: Meigs
etymology: Named for Return J. Meigs Sr., an officer in the Continental Army.

name: Decatur
etymology: Named for Commodore Stephen Decatur, a naval leader in the War of 1812 and who defeated the Barbary Coast pirates at Tripoli in 1815.

name: Polk
etymology: Named for James K. Polk before he became President; he was governor of Tennessee at the time the county was established.

name: Van Buren
etymology: Named for U.S. President Martin Van Buren (1782–1862).

name: Macon
etymology: Named for Nathaniel Macon, a U.S. Congressman and President pro tempore of the U.S. Senate.

name: Putnam
etymology: Named for Revolutionary War general Israel Putnam.

name: Lewis
etymology: Named for Meriwether Lewis, a co-leader of the Lewis and Clark Expedition.

name: Grundy
etymology: Named for Felix Grundy (1777–1840), Tennessee senator that served as the 13th United States Attorney General.

name: Hancock
etymology: Named for John Hancock (1737–1793), president of the Continental Congress and the first signer of the Declaration of Independence.

name: DeKalb
etymology: Named for Baron Johann de Kalb (1721–1780), a German soldier who fought on the side of the Americans in the Revolutionary War.

name: Scott
etymology: Named for General Winfield Scott.

name: Cheatham
etymology: Named for Edward Cheatham, state legislator.

name: Clay
etymology: Named for Henry Clay (1777–1852), U.S. legislator from Kentucky.

name: Hamblen
etymology: Named for Hezekiah Hamblen, an early settler.

name: Trousdale
etymology: Named for William Trousdale, Creek and Mexican–American War soldier and officer, state senator and Governor of Tennessee.

name: Crockett
etymology: Named for Davy Crockett (1786–1836), frontier humorist, congressman, and defender of the Alamo.

name: Houston
etymology: Named for Sam Houston (1793–1863), 2nd and 4th President of the Republic of Texas, U.S. Senator, and 7th Governor of Texas.

name: Moore
etymology: Named for William Moore, an officer during the War of 1812 and later a state legislator.

name: Chester
etymology: Named for Tennessee state legislator Robert I. Chester.

name: Pickett
etymology: Named for Howard L. Pickett, state legislator.

name: Union
etymology: Named either for its creation from parts of five counties or to memorialize East Tennessee’s support for preservation of the Union in the years before the Civil War.

name: Obion
etymology: From the Obion River, named either from a Native American word meaning “many forks” or from an Irish-French trapper named O’Brien.

name: Lake
etymology: Named for Reelfoot Lake, the county’s most significant geographic feature along with the Mississippi River.

name: Grainger
etymology: Named for Mary Grainger Blount, wife of William Blount and “first lady” of the Southwest Territory, which later became Tennessee.

name: Refugio
etymology: Named for the city of Refugio, Texas, itself named for the Rancho Nuestra Señora del Refugio.

name: Fort Bend
etymology: Named for Fort Bend, a military blockhouse built at a bend in the Brazos River.
ety1: Named for Fort Bend, a military blockhouse
ety2: built at a bend in the Brazos River

name: Mason
etymology: Named for Fort Mason, itself named for George Thomson Mason, a U.S. Army lieutenant killed during the Mexican–American War.

name: Rockwall
etymology: Named for Rockwall, Texas, which was named after rock walls thought to be man-made but later found to be natural clastic dikes.

name: Live Oak
etymology: Named for the Texas live oak tree under which the petition for a new county was signed.

name: Freestone
etymology: Named because water in the area was found to be free of minerals.

name: Nacogdoches
etymology: Named for the Nacogdoche tribe of Caddo Native Americans.

name: Hopkins
etymology: Named for Named for the family of David Hopkins, an early settler in the area.

name: Jack
etymology: Named for Patrick Churchill Jack and his brother William Houston Jack, both soldiers of the Texas Revolution.

name: Hardeman
etymology: Named for Bailey Hardeman and Thomas Jones Hardeman, two early Texas politicians and legislators.

name: Hardin
etymology: Named for the Hardin family, settlers of nearby Liberty County.

name: Wichita
etymology: Named for the Wichita people.

name: Upton
etymology: Named for brothers John C. and William F. Upton, both Colonels in the Confederate army.

name: Armstrong
etymology: Named for any one of several Texas pioneer families.

name: Garza
etymology: The name of a resident pioneer family.

name: Liberty
etymology: Named for the philosophical ideal.

name: Midland
etymology: Named for its location midway between Fort Worth and El Paso on the Texas and Pacific Railroad.

name: Austin
etymology: Named for Stephen Fuller Austin, the person who facilitated the Anglo American colonization of Texas and is known as the Father of Texas.

name: Harris
etymology: Named for John Richardson Harris, an early settler of the area.

name: Jackson
etymology: Named for Andrew Jackson, the 7th President of the United States.

name: Jasper
etymology: Named for William Jasper, a hero of the Battle of Sullivan’s Island during the American Revolutionary War.

name: Jefferson
etymology: Named for Thomas Jefferson, the third President of the United States.

name: Milam
etymology: Named for Benjamin Rush Milam, an early Texas colonizer and soldier killed in the Texas Revolution.

name: Shelby
etymology: Named for Isaac Shelby, the first Governor of Kentucky.

name: Washington
etymology: Named for George Washington, first President of the United States.

name: Fannin
etymology: Named for Colonel James Fannin (1809–1836), hero of the Texas Revolution.

name: Houston
etymology: Named for Sam Houston (1793–1863), 2nd and 4th President of the Republic of Texas, U.S. Senator, and 7th Governor of Texas.

name: Montgomery
etymology: Named for Richard Montgomery, an officer during the American Revolutionary War.

name: Robertson
etymology: Named for Sterling C. Robertson, empresario during Mexican Texas.

name: Harrison
etymology: Named for Jonas Harrison, a lawyer and Texas revolutionary.

name: Bowie
etymology: Named for James Bowie, the legendary knife fighter who died at the Battle of the Alamo.

name: Travis
etymology: Named in honor of William Barret Travis, commander of the Republic of Texas forces at the Battle of the Alamo.

name: Burleson
etymology: Named for Edward Burleson, a general and statesman of the Texas Revolution.

name: Rusk
etymology: Named for Thomas Jefferson Rusk, political and military leader of the Republic of Texas.

name: Anderson
etymology: ”Kenneth Lewis Anderson, the last vice president of the Republic of Texas.

name: Calhoun
etymology: Named for John C. Calhoun, the U.S. statesman, seventh vice president of the United States, Secretary of State, and U.S. senator from South Carolina.

name: Cass
etymology: Named for Lewis Cass, Governor of Michigan and U.S. cabinet member.

name: Collin
etymology: Named for Collin McKinney (1766–1861), an author of the Texas Declaration of Independence.

name: Dallam
etymology: Named for James Wilmer Dallam, a lawyer and newspaper publisher.

name: Denton
etymology: Named for John B. Denton, a preacher, lawyer, and soldier.

name: Grayson
etymology: Named for Peter Wagener Grayson, attorney general of the Republic of Texas.

name: Grimes
etymology: Named for Jesse Grimes, a signer of the Texas Declaration of Independence and an early settler of the county.

name: Henderson
etymology: Named for James Pinckney Henderson, first Attorney General of the Republic of Texas.

name: Hunt
etymology: Named for Memucan Hunt, Jr., first Republic of Texas Minister to the United States.

name: Leon
etymology: Named for Martín De León, the founder of Victoria, Texas.

name: Navarro
etymology: Named for José Antonio Navarro, a Tejano leader in the Texas Revolution who signed the Texas Declaration of Independence.

name: Newton
etymology: Named after Sgt. John Newton of the American Revolutionary War.

name: Polk
etymology: Named for James K. Polk, President of the United States 1845–49.

name: Smith
etymology: Named for James Smith, a general during the Texas Revolution.

name: Titus
etymology: Named for Andrew Jackson Titus, an early settler.

name: Tyler
etymology: Named for John Tyler, the tenth President of the United States.

name: Upshur
etymology: Named for Abel P. Upshur, who was U.S. Secretary of State during President John Tyler’s administration.

name: Walker
etymology: Named for Samuel Hamilton Walker, soldier.

name: Wharton
etymology: Named for William H. Wharton and John Austin Wharton, brothers and Republic of Texas leaders.

name: Caldwell
etymology: Probably named for Mathew Caldwell, a signer of the Texas Declaration of Independence and soldier during the Texas Revolution.

name: Cameron
etymology: Named for Ewen Cameron, a soldier during the Texas Revolution.

name: Cooke
etymology: Named for William Gordon Cooke, a soldier during the Texas Revolution.

name: Gillespie
etymology: Named for Robert Addison Gillespie (1815–1846), a Texas Ranger, Native American fighter, merchant and soldier

name: Hays
etymology: Named for John Coffee Hays, a Texas Ranger and an officer during the Mexican–American War.

name: Kaufman
etymology: Named for David Spangler Kaufman, a legislator and diplomat of the Republic of Texas and later a U.S. Congressman.

name: Starr
etymology: Named for James Harper Starr, director of the postal service of the Trans-Mississippi Department.

name: Van Zandt
etymology: Named for Isaac Van Zandt, a member of the Congress of the Republic of Texas.

name: Webb
etymology: Named for James Webb, who served as Secretary of the Treasury, Secretary of State, and Attorney General of the Republic of Texas

name: Williamson
etymology: Named for Robert McAlpin Williamson, Texas Ranger and judge.

name: Tarrant
etymology: Named for of General Edward H. Tarrant, of the Republic of Texas militia.

name: Bell
etymology: Named for Peter Hansborough Bell, the third governor of Texas.

name: Ellis
etymology: Named for Richard Ellis, president of the convention that produced the Texas Declaration of Independence.

name: Kinney
etymology: Named for Henry Lawrence Kinney, an early settler of Texas.

name: McLennan
etymology: Named for Neil McLennan, an early settler.

name: Trinity
etymology: Named after the Trinity River (Texas).

name: Wood
etymology: Named for George Tyler Wood, second Governor of Texas.

name: Burnet
etymology: Named for David Gouverneur Burnet, the first president of the Republic of Texas.

name: Hidalgo
etymology: Named for Father Miguel Hidalgo y Costilla, the priest who raised the call for MexicO’s independence from Spain in 1810.

name: Hill
etymology: Named for George Washington Hill, a Secretary of War and Secretary of the Navy for the Republic of Texas.

name: Madison
etymology: Named for James Madison, the 4th President of the United States.

name: Coryell
etymology: Named for James Coryell, a frontiersman who was killed by Native Americans.

name: Johnson
etymology: Named for Middleton Johnson, a Texas Ranger, soldier, and politician.

name: Karnes
etymology: Named for Henry Karnes, a soldier of the Texas Revolution.

name: Parker
etymology: Named for Isaac Parker, a Texas state representative.

name: Brown
etymology: Named for Henry Stevenson Brown, a commander at the Battle of Velasco prior to the Texas Revolution.

name: Erath
etymology: Named for George Bernard Erath, an early surveyor and a soldier at the Battle of San Jacinto during the Texas Revolution.

name: Kerr
etymology: Named for James Kerr, an early settler and legislator of the Republic of Texas.

name: Lamar
etymology: Named for Mirabeau B. Lamar, the second President of the Republic of Texas.

name: Maverick
etymology: Named for Samuel Augustus Maverick, a lawyer and rancher whose stubborn independence, allegedly for refusing to brand his cattle, is the origin of the word “maverick”.

name: McCulloch
etymology: Named for Benjamin McCulloch, a Texas Ranger and Confederate general during the American Civil War.

name: Wise
etymology: Named for Henry A. Wise, Confederate general and later politician.

name: Young
etymology: Named for William Cocke Young, an early Texas settler and soldier.

name: Bee
etymology: Named for Barnard Elliott Bee, Sr., a secretary of state of the Republic of Texas.

name: Clay
etymology: Named for Henry Clay (1777–1852), U.S. legislator from Kentucky.

name: Montague
etymology: Named for Daniel Montague, a state senator and early surveyor of the county.

name: Archer
etymology: Named for Branch Tanner Archer, a commissioner for the Republic of Texas.

name: Baylor
etymology: Named for Henry Weidner Baylor, a surgeon in the Texas Rangers during the Mexican–American War.

name: Callahan
etymology: Named for James Hughes Callahan, a soldier during the Texas Revolution.

name: Chambers
etymology: Named for Thomas Jefferson Chambers, an early lawyer in Texas.

name: Coleman
etymology: Named for Robert M. Coleman, a signer of the Texas Declaration of Independence and soldier at the Battle of San Jacinto.

name: Dallas
etymology: Named for George Mifflin Dallas, eleventh vice president of the United States.

name: Dimmit
etymology: Named for Philip Dimmitt, a major figure in the Texas Revolution.

name: Duval
etymology: Named for Burr H. Duval (1809–1836), a soldier in the Texas Revolution who died in the Goliad Massacre.

name: Eastland
etymology: Named for William Mosby Eastland, a soldier during the Texas Revolution and the only officer to die as a result of the so-called “Black Bean” executions following the Mier expedition.

name: Edwards
etymology: Named for Haden Harrison Edwards, an early settler.

name: Hamilton
etymology: Named for James Hamilton Jr., 53rd Governor of South Carolina (1830–1832) who gave financial aid to the Republic of Texas.

name: Haskell
etymology: Named for Charles Ready Haskell, who was killed in the Goliad massacre.

name: Jones
etymology: Named for Anson Jones, the last President of the Republic of Texas.

name: Kimble
etymology: Named for George C. Kimble, who died at the Battle of the Alamo during the Texas Revolution.

name: Knox
etymology: Named for Henry Knox, a general during the American Revolutionary War and the first U.S. Secretary of War.

name: Lamb
etymology: Named for George A. Lamb, who died in the Battle of San Jacinto during the Texas Revolution.

name: McMullen
etymology: Named for John McMullen, an Irish founder of a colony in Texas.

name: Menard
etymology: Named for Michel Branamour Menard, the founder of Galveston, Texas.

name: Runnels
etymology: Named for Hiram Runnels, Mississippi politician.

name: Shackelford
etymology: Named for Jack Shackelford, doctor and soldier of the Texas Revolution.

name: Stephens
etymology: Named for Alexander Stephens, Vice President of the Confederate States of America.

name: Taylor
etymology: Named for Edward Taylor, George Taylor, and James Taylor, three brothers who died at the Battle of the Alamo.

name: Throckmorton
etymology: Named for William Throckmorton, an early Collin County settler.

name: Wilbarger
etymology: Named for Josiah Pugh Wilbarger and Mathias Wilbarger, early settler.

name: Marion
etymology: Named for Francis Marion, a Continental Army officer nicknamed the “Swamp Fox” for his activity in the Southern Theater of the American Revolutionary War.

name: Wilson
etymology: Named for James Charles Wilson, early settler.

name: Kendall
etymology: Named for George Wilkins Kendall, a journalist and Mexican–American War correspondent.

name: Hood
etymology: Named for John Bell Hood, a Confederate lieutenant general.

name: Deaf Smith
etymology: Named for Erastus Deaf Smith (1787–1837), a scout during the Texas Revolution.

name: Rains
etymology: Named for Emory Rains, politician in the Republic of Texas.

name: Gregg
etymology: Named for John Gregg, a Confederate general killed in action during the American Civil War.

name: Waller
etymology: Named for Edwin Waller, entrepreneur and town planner.

name: Camp
etymology: Named for John Lafayette Camp, a Texas state politician.

name: Lee
etymology: Named for Robert E. Lee, the highest-ranking general of the Confederate States Army during the American Civil War.

name: Tom Green
etymology: Named for Thomas Green, a Confederate brigadier general.

name: Crockett
etymology: Named for Davy Crockett (1786–1836), frontier humorist, congressman, and defender of the Alamo.

name: Franklin
etymology: Generally believed to have been named after Judge Benjamin C. Franklin, the first appointed justice in the Republic of Texas.

name: Morris
etymology: Named for W.W. Morris, a prominent attorney in east Texas.

name: Somervell
etymology: Named for Alexander Somervell, Secretary of War of the Republic of Texas.

name: Andrew
etymology: ”Richard Andrews, the first Texan soldier to die in the Texas Revolution.

name: Bailey
etymology: Named for Peter James Bailey, a defender of the Alamo.

name: Borden
etymology: Named for Gail Borden, Jr., a businessman, publisher, and surveyor in Texas who invented condensed milk.

name: Briscoe
etymology: Named for Andrew Briscoe, a soldier during the Texas Revolution.

name: Carson
etymology: Named for Samuel Price Carson, the first secretary of state of the Republic of Texas.

name: Castro
etymology: Named for Henri Castro, consul general to France for the Republic of Texas and founder of a colony in Texas.

name: Childress
etymology: Named for George Childress (1804–1841), one of the authors of the Texas Declaration of Independence.

name: Cochran
etymology: Named for Robert E. Cochran (1810–1836), a defender of the Alamo.

name: Collingsworth
etymology: Named for James Collinsworth, a signer of the Texas Declaration of Independence and first chief justice of the Republic of Texas.

name: Cottle
etymology: Named for George Washington Cottle, who died defending the Alamo.

name: Crosby
etymology: Named for Stephen Crosby, a land commissioner.

name: Dawson
etymology: Named for Nicholas Mosby Dawson, a soldier of the Texas Revolution and victim of the Dawson Massacre.

name: DeWitt
etymology: Named for Green DeWitt, an empresario who founded an early colony in Texas.

name: Dickens
etymology: Named for J. Dickens, who died at the Battle of the Alamo.

name: Donley
etymology: Named for Stockton P. Donley, a frontier lawyer.

name: Fisher
etymology: Named for Samuel Rhoads Fisher, a signer of the Texas Declaration of Independence.

name: Floyd
etymology: Named for Dolphin Ward Floyd, who died defending the Alamo during the Texas Revolution.

name: Gaines
etymology: Named for James Gaines, merchant who signed the Texas Declaration of Independence.

name: Gray
etymology: Named for Peter W. Gray, a Confederate lawyer and soldier in the Civil War.

name: Hale
etymology: Named for Lieutenant John C. Hale, hero of the Battle of San Jacinto during the Texas Revolution.

name: Hall
etymology: Named for Warren D.C. Hall, Secretary of War for the Republic of Texas.

name: Hansford
etymology: Named for John M. Hansford, a Texas state congressman and judge.

name: Hartley
etymology: Named for Oliver C. Hartley and his brother, Rufus K. Hartley, two early Texas legislators.

name: Hemphill
etymology: Named for John Hemphill, Chief Justice of the Texas Supreme Court and a U.S. Senator.

name: Hockley
etymology: Named for George Washington Hockley, a Secretary of War of the Republic of Texas.

name: Howard
etymology: Named for Volney E. Howard, U.S. Congressman from Texas.

name: Hutchinson
etymology: Named for Andrew Hutchinson, an early attorney in Texas.

name: Kent
etymology: Named for Andrew Kent, who died at the Battle of the Alamo during the Texas Revolution.

name: King
etymology: Named for William Philip King, who died at the Battle of the Alamo during the Texas Revolution.

name: La Salle
etymology: Named for René-Robert Cavelier, Sieur de La Salle, an early French explorer of the Mississippi River.

name: Lipscomb
etymology: Named for Abner Smith Lipscomb, a judge and Secretary of State of the Republic of Texas.

name: Lubbock
etymology: Named for Thomas Saltus Lubbock, a Texas Ranger and Confederate soldier during the American Civil War.

name: Lynn
etymology: Named for William Lynn, a soldier believed to have died defending the Alamo.

name: Martin
etymology: Named for Wylie Martin, an early settler of the region.

name: Mitchell
etymology: Named for Asa and Eli Mitchell, early settlers of Stephen F. Austin’s colony.

name: Moore
etymology: Named for Edwin Ward Moore, a Republic of Texas naval officer.

name: Motley
etymology: Named for Junius William Mottley, a signer of the Texas Declaration of Independence.

name: Nolan
etymology: Named for Philip Nolan, one of the first American traders to visit Texas.

name: Ochiltree
etymology: Named for Col. William Beck Ochiltree, Republic of Texas secretary of the treasury.

name: Oldham
etymology: Named for William Simpson Oldham Sr., Texas pioneer and Confederate Senator.

name: Parmer
etymology: Named for Martin Parmer, signatory to the Texas Declaration of Independence.

name: Potter
etymology: Named for Robert Potter, signer of the Texas Declaration of Independence and Texas Secretary of the Navy.

name: Randall
etymology: Named for Horace Randal (sic), Confederate soldier.

name: Roberts
etymology: Named for Oran Milo Roberts, 17th Governor of Texas.

name: Scurry
etymology: Named for William Read Scurry, Confederate general.

name: Sherman
etymology: Named for Founding Father Roger Sherman.

name: Stonewall
etymology: Named for Lieutenant General Thomas Jonathan “Stonewall” Jackson

name: Swisher
etymology: Named for James G. Swisher, a soldier of the Texas Revolution.

name: Terry
etymology: Named for Benjamin Franklin Terry, a colonel in the Confederate Army.

name: Wheeler
etymology: Named for Royall T. Wheeler, judge.

name: Yoakum
etymology: Named for Henderson King Yoakum, a Texas historian.

name: Sutton
etymology: Named for John S. Sutton, Confederate officer.

name: Reeves
etymology: Named for George R. Reeves, Speaker of the House of the State of Texas and Confederate colonel.

name: Brewster

etymology: Named for the Teton Range.

name: Uinta
etymology: Named for the Uintah, a Native American tribe associated with the Ute people.

name: Crook
etymology: Named for General George Crook (1828–1980), a U.S. Army officer who served in the American Civil War and various Native American Wars.

name: Johnson
etymology: Named for E.P. Johnson, a Cheyenne attorney.

name: Fremont
etymology: Named for John C. Frémont, an explorer of the American West, officer during the Mexican–American War, and presidential candidate in 1856.

name: Converse
etymology: Named for A. R. Converse, a banker and rancher from Cheyenne.

name: Sheridan
etymology: Named for Philip Sheridan, U.S. Army general.

name: Weston
etymology: Named for Jefferson B. Weston, geologist and surveyor.

name: Campbell
etymology: Named for John Allen Campbell (1835–1880), first governor of the Wyoming Territory (1869–1875); or for John Archibald Campbell, a governor of the Wyoming Territory and associate justice of the United States Supreme Court; or Robert Campbell, an explorer of the area.

name: Lincoln
etymology: Named for Abraham Lincoln, the 16th President of the United States.

name: Carbon
etymology: Named for coal deposits in the region.

name: Natrona
etymology: Named for the natron, or soda deposits in the county.

name: Sweetwater
etymology: Named for the Sweetwater River.

name: Hot Springs
etymology: Named for naturally occurring hot springs located in the county seat of Thermopolis.
